#: ../../../manual/game_engine/performance/introduction.rst:6
# 5906ab889ad843c289aaf4694811d9dd
msgid "When developing games, game engineers, software and hardware developers uses some tools to fine tune their games to specific platforms and operating systems, defining a basic usage scenario whereas the users would have the best possible experience with the game."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/game_engine/performance/introduction.rst:10
# 04df12a937cf47908047194c1d8001c9
msgid "Most of these tools, are software tools available for the specific Game Engines whereas the games were being developed and will run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/game_engine/performance/introduction.rst:13
# 57330401bcef4121b385e99255ddd98b
msgid "Blender Game Engine also comes with some visual tools to fine tune the games being developed, so the game developers could test the best usage scenario and minimum software and hardware requirements to run the game."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/game_engine/performance/introduction.rst:17
# 3de77c0b0d044e00bb6b955312504289
msgid "In Blender, those tools are available at the *System* and *Display* tab of *Render* Context in the *Properties Window*. There are options for specific performance adjusts and measurements, ways to control the frame rate or the way the contents are rendered in Blender window (game viewport) while the game runs, as well as controls for maintainnig geometry allocated in graphic cards memory."
msgstr ""

